{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489844"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:32:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:32:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"759"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582740"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:53:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:53:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"759"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/759"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.03,0.06,0.71,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"759"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105762"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/759"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"759"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88230"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5364"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6129"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6150"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6357"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16205"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38805"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43815"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44979"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105762"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic seeking counselling regarding screening for bowel cancer. She is completely asymptomatic and has no digestive tract symptoms. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is very concerned because her 70-year-old mother has recently been diagnosed with colorectal cancer and is the first person in the family to have developed the disease. She would like to undertake further investigations to assess for colorectal cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Faecal occult blood test now and biennially thereafter","Colonoscopy now and faecal occult blood test biennially thereafter","Five-yearly colonoscopy starting now","Biennial faecal occult blood test from the age of 45","Five-yearly colonoscopy starting age 60"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient falls into the category of slightly increased risk for colorectal cancer based on her family history. She has one first-degree relative (her mother) diagnosed with colorectal cancer at the age of 60 or over. According to current guidelines, this places her in in category 1 (average risk).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiennial faecal occult blood test from the age of 45\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate advice for this patient. The current recommendation for population screening in Australia is biennial immunochemical faecal occult blood test (iFOBT) in asymptomatic individuals, starting from age 45 years to age 74 years. It is important to note the recommendations are for ages 45 to 74 however patients are only routinely invited to participate at age 50. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFaecal occult blood test now and biennially thereafter\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as the patient is only 42 years old. Starting screening now would be premature given her risk profile and lack of symptoms. She should be reassured and advised that her risk is similar to that of the general population.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy now and faecal occult blood test biennially thereafter\u003C/strong\u003E is too aggressive for this patient\u0027s risk profile. Colonoscopy is typically reserved for those at moderate or high risk, as a follow-up to positive FOBT results and in symptomatic patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFive-yearly colonoscopy starting now\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for this patient\u0027s risk level. This regimen would typically be recommended for individuals at moderately increased risk, such as those with a first-degree relative diagnosed with colorectal cancer before age 55.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFive-yearly colonoscopy starting age 60\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as it delays screening too long and uses a more invasive method than necessary for this patient\u0027s risk level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe current colorectal cancer risk categories and screening recommendations based on family history are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 1 - similar risk as the general population\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with no family history of colorectal cancer OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne 1st-degree relative with CRC \u226560 years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: FOBT should be completed every 2 years from 45 years old as per usual screening protocol. Colonoscopy is generally not recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 2 - moderately increased risk\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with one 1st-degree relative CRC diagnosed \u0026lt;60 years OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age or one 1st-degree and one or more 2nd-degree relatives diagnosed at any age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: Colonoscopy should be offered 5 yearly starting at \u003Cstrong\u003E10 years younger\u003C/strong\u003E than the earliest diagnosis of CRC in a 1st-degree relative, or age \u003Cstrong\u003E50 \u003C/strong\u003E(whichever is earliest).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 3 - high risk, excluding hereditary cancer syndromes\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic with two 1st-degree and one 2nd-degree relative with colorectal cancer, with at least one diagnosed before 50 years old OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives and two or more 2nd-degree relatives diagnosed with CRC at any age OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThree or more 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: refer to the familial cancer clinic for genetic assessment before a screening decision is made if Lynch syndrome has not been excluded. If Lynch syndrome is excluded, colonoscopy should be offered every 5 years starting at \u003Cstrong\u003E10 years younger\u003C/strong\u003E than the earliest age of diagnosis of colorectal cancer in a first-degree relative or age \u003Cstrong\u003E40 \u003C/strong\u003Eyears (whichever is earliest)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Individuals with one first-degree relative diagnosed with colorectal cancer at age 60 or over are considered average risk (category 1)","Average risk patients should be screened by faecal occult blood testing every two years from the age of 45","Risk stratification is crucial in determining the appropriate colorectal cancer screening strategy."],"references":["RACGP. Guidance for preventative activities in general practice: colorectal cancer. 2024. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/preventive-activities-in-general-practice/cancer/colorectal-cancer","Cancer Council Australia. Clinical practice guidelines for the prevention, early detection and management of colorectal cancer: Risk and screening based on family history. 2024. Available at: https://app.magicapp.org/#/guideline/jz5DdE"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88230"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"759"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88230"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-13T07:49:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-13T07:50:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"759"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105762"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data